(personal experience, censorship in the library has cost me precious time, and has stolen from me) Tj
T* (parts of my life. Growing up in a small town, where ideas of gender and sexuality were somewhat) Tj
T* (firmly set, any search for dissenting opinion was often fruitless. When I visited my school's) Tj
T* (library, as a child searching for answers about my sexuality, I found little aid. Around the) Tj
T* (library were a thousand stories of a man and woman falling in love, but never did I find a fairy) Tj
T* (tale of two princes. It was not until I left the school that I found that such books did exist) Tj
T* (in my old school library, but kept removed, off the shelves, restricted. More insulting than) Tj
T* (finding books of @CAPS4 issues completely unrepresented was to find that they were treated so) Tj
T* (separately. Here lies the problem. Some people believe that if minority opinions or values are) Tj
T* (unrepresented, they will disappear. Such is the point of censorship: ignoring an issue or a) Tj
T* (life-choice to the point of extinction. But books cannot shout their values. They cannot shove) Tj
T* (information down our throats. Books must be read, we must give our consent to their knowledge.) Tj
T* (Unlike an advertisement that might accost us unawares, we must pick up a book and open it to) Tj
T* (receive its guidance. If my library had done its job and given me the guidance I sought, I would) Tj
T* (have grown so much more easily. I would have learned not only how to express and accept myself,) Tj
T* (but I might have grown to more easily accept others as well. In the past few years, with the) Tj
T* (effects of @CAPS5 @CAPS6 @CAPS7 reaching the newest generation, @LOCATION1 has searched for ways) Tj
T* (to pay homage to the victims of the violence of @CAPS8 and of the @CAPS9. What the country) Tj
T* (finds, however, is that it cannot effectively memorialize the tragedies. In trying construct a) Tj
T* (monument, the government and culture find that they have little to build off of. The products of) Tj
T* (murder and book-burning have resulted in an emptiness, a void. As such, architects have created) Tj
T* (what @MONTH1 be called 'anti-monuments', commemorating a void to posterity to memorialize what) Tj
T* (was lost. One of the most powerful, to me at least, appears in the form of a negative bookshelf:) Tj
T* (a solid wall, with gaping holes in the form of book spines, ranging across the rows. Such is the) Tj
T* (knowledge lost from book-burning. We cannot even describe what is lost, for the knowledge has) Tj
T* (vanished. We must ask, what are we missing? What views, what prose, what beauty has been taking) Tj
T* (from us while we continue living, never having the chance to glimpse it? This is the effect of) Tj
T* (library censorship. To remove a book from its natural and rightful place on a shelf is to set) Tj
T* (its words aflame. Once it is gone, it will be forgotten. To protect our posterity, to enlighten) Tj
T* (our descendants, we must work to preserve all books, any book that appears offensive, or) Tj
T* (disgusting, or brave, or new. Let the reader decide its value. Let the person in search of) Tj
T* (answers pick it up or leave it behind. Give the book a chance for it @MONTH1 have a power that) Tj
T* (is unrealized. Leave the libraries as they are, as the monuments to the preservation and) Tj
T* (progression of knowledge and wisdom.) Tj
